Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Chop the @potatoes{3} into 2cm wide wedges (no need to peel).

Pop onto a large (lined) #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{to taste} and season
with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}. Toss to coat.

Spread out in a single layer and roast on the top shelf of your #oven{} until
golden, ~{25-35%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Cut @broccoli{1} into florets. Halve larger florets.

Halve, peel and thinly slice @onion{1}.

Peel and grate @garlic{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Place your hand flat on top of the @Irish chicken breast{320%grams} and slice
through horizontally to make two thin steaks.

> Notice a stronger smell from your chicken? Don't worry, this is normal due
> to vacuum packing we use to keep it fresh.

Place a #pan{} over a high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste} (give it a wipe
if you like).

Add the broccoli and onion and season with salt and pepper.

Fry until tender and slightly charred, ~{2-3%minutes} then add garlic and fry
for ~{1%minute}.

Add a splash of @water{to taste} and immediately cover with a #lid{} or some
#foil{}. Cook until the broccoli is tender, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Remove from the pan and cover to keep warm.

Return the pan to medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

When hot, add the chicken steaks and season with salt and pepper.

Cook through, ~{3-6%minutes} each side (cook in batches if your pan is getting
crowded).

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its
> packaging. Chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Meanwhile, in a #small bowl{} mix the @BBQ sauce{2%sachets}, @honey{2%sachets}
and @water{25%ml}. Stir to combine.

When the chicken is cooked, add the BBQ sauce to the pan with a knob of
@?butter{} if you have any.

Carefully use a #spoon{} to baste the chicken in the BBQ sauce.

Plate up the BBQ chicken with the broccoli and wedges alongside.

Drizzle over any remaining sauce in the pan.